<span class="Greek"><span id="ix.ii.xv-p26.4"></span>ς</span>, whose
value is *six*, and which was called <span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ii.xv-p26.5"></span>ἐπίσημον</span> by the Greeks.

<span id="fn_2846"></span>[338:2847](0010711.htm#fr_2846.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p27.1"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p28"></span> Referring to *Aletheia*, which, in
Greek, contains seven letters.

<span id="fn_2847"></span>[338:2848](0010711.htm#fr_2847.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p28.1"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p29"></span> By these seven powers are meant the
seven heavens (also called angels), formed by the Demiurge.

<span id="fn_2848"></span>[338:2849](0010711.htm#fr_2848.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p30.1"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p31"></span> We here follow the text of Hippolytus:
the ordinary text and the old Latin read, “So does the soul of infants,
weeping and mourning over Marcus, deify him.”

<span id="fn_2849"></span>[338:2850](0010711.htm#fr_2849.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p31.1"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p32"></span> [Ps. viii.
2](../../../bib/kjv/psa008.htm#002.md)<span id="ix.ii.xv-p32.1"></span>.

<span id="fn_2850"></span>[338:2851](0010711.htm#fr_2850.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p32.2"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p33"></span> [Ps. xix.
1](../../../bib/kjv/psa019.htm#001.md)<span id="ix.ii.xv-p33.1"></span>.

<span id="fn_2851"></span>[338:2852](0010711.htm#fr_2851.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p33.3"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p34"></span> The text is here altogether uncertain:
we have given the probable meaning.

<span id="fn_2852"></span>[338:2853](0010711.htm#fr_2852.md) <span
id="ix.ii.xv-p35.1"></span>

<span id="ix.ii.xv-p36"></span> That is, the name of Soter, the perfect
result of the whole Pleroma.

